description.plain:
“Moral of the Story” is Ashe’s farewell to a past relationship. It is the first release since her debut EP, The Rabbit Hole and the title track to her two-part EP series.

The track saw its peak in early February 2020, almost a year after its initial release, when it was featured in a pivotal scene in the teen Netflix film To All The Boys 2: P.S. I Still Love You. Genius said in its own article that the song “saw an immediate spike on Genius, skyrocketing from 268 [daily] pageviews to 13,152 overnight.”

Some mistakes get made
 That’s alright, that’s okay

From Ashe:
“I think that moral of the story, this line in particular, I wanted to say, “I’ve been through all the phases of grieving, the denial, the anger, the trying to get back together with a person, all of those phases that are, I mean, healthy to go through, but that final acceptance moment is a really cool place to be in.” And yeah, just realizing, “Hey, I needed to go through what I needed to go through, and as shitty as it was, I know that I’m better for it.””

Some mistakes get made
 That’s alright, that’s okay
 You can think that you’re in love
 When you’re really just in pain

From Ashe:
“I think being alone is a very isolating and vulnerable experience and it can make you feel very shameful and sometimes it’s easier to be in a relationship than to be alone. And I think that’s where the line was like, “You can think that you’re in love when you’re really just in pain.” I think that this is the most twistable lyric for a lot of different people. For me that’s what it meant. But I think other people have a completely different interpretation, which is cool. Just thinking that you’re in a passionate relationship when you’re actually in just turmoil. I mean mistaking, passion for love.”
In the end, it’s better for me
People say its better to make mistakes to learn from them instead of being uneducated, i think thats what Ashe means here

Some mistakes get made
 That’s alright, that’s okay
 In the end, it’s better for me
 That’s the moral of the story, babe

I think that moral of the story, this line in particular, I wanted to say, “I’ve been through all the phases of grieving, the denial, the anger, the trying to get back together with a person, all of those phases that are, I mean, healthy to go through, but that final acceptance moment is a really cool place to be in.” And yeah, just realizing, “Hey, I needed to go through what I needed to go through, and as shitty as it was, I know that I’m better for it.”

With all the bumps in the road, all the negatives and positives that were experienced, they were a form of lesson. Every relationship is a story/chapter in someones life; with every relationship, just like a story/chapter, you learn something about yourself.

I said, ”Young people fall in love
 With the wrong people sometimes”

It feels like it’s just super relatable to all of us young kids because how many of us fall in love and your first love, especially when you’re in high school or something or right at the beginning of college. Man, you fall deep and you only know what you know at the time. So you don’t know anything else than the love you’ve experienced. So it’s just mind-blowingly crushing and I think it’s been… People have been really cool and come up to me and talked about even like, “My best friend, I was in a toxic friend relationship and I was like, ‘I got to break this off.’” So that’s cool.

The simple saying has a strong meaning. Young people like high schoolers and whatnots get into relationships and since they have no idea what love actually is and whats supposed to be a good relationship. This leads onto the young ones ending up falling in love with the the wrong people who end up hurting them and breaking their hearts in the end.

Thought we could really do this
 But really, I was foolish
 Hindsight, it’s obvious

I’m now a little bit past this moment and going, “Oh, I was 21 when I met you. Oh, we did not stand a chance. I had so much growing up and learning to do, I’m a completely different human being than I was when we met.” And so there’s a lot of me that’s like, “Of course that wasn’t going to work.” But when you’re in it, you’re in love and you’re like, “Oh, everything’s great.”

She kept telling herself that there was a chance, that they would get through it in the end, but deep down inside and even to the end, she knew she was kidding herself. She knew it was obvious, but didn’t care. She kept wanting and trying to make it work for them.

God, I really tried to
 Blindsided, addicted

I became addicted to the chaos of our relationship. When you’re in something sort of toxic, there’s like there’s a cycle you go through. You get really angry with each other and then there’s a big blow up and then there’s a honeymoon phase and then the cycle continues and you start getting really used to being miserable and thinking that’s normal.
Even when she realized she didn’t know him, she kept trying; she didn’t stop even though she was blinded with love and was addicted to it. She kept trying because she was in love and hooked on it.
So I never really knew you

First lyric of the song and I’m already like, “Oh, it’s so loaded.” I think I fell in love with the idea of the person that I was with and slowly but surely, it was changing into something I didn’t recognize. And so yeah, it just ended up feeling like a lie. So it felt like I never really knew him, which is super sad.

She never saw the true colors of who she was with. Even though she’s been with him for who knows how long, in the end, when she looked back, she realized she never really knew who he was when she was with him.

That could be a load of shit
 But I just need to tell you all

I think the whole song in general is a pretty mature way of looking at love lost. I think the bridge is a very human moment of going, “but also fuck all that.” This also really sucked and it’s better to have loved and loss. Well also, is it? Just that. Sorry, maybe it comes from a more immature place, but it’s as human as the rest of all of our emotions.

Talking with my mother
 She said, “Where’d you find this guy?”

My mom is way less cut throat than my divorce attorney. She’s just like a sweetheart and really loved my ex. She was sweet about it. But when things started to go down and I told her more details about what was happening, she was like, “What’s going on?” So, that’s basically that line.

description.plain:
“Till Forever Falls Apart” is an eruptive ballad about loving someone through every obstacle, and knowing that your love will never break. Throughout the song, Ashe and FINNEAS use metaphors about the end of the world to paint this picture. Although most contemporary pop writes about love in a romantic context, this song could be viewed in a platonic-friendship perspective, making it stand out from the over-saturated landscape of romantic ballads.
Sonically, the song has a vintage feel, with heavy drums and guitar throughout.

In a livestream counting down the music video’s premiere, Ashe stated that she was inspired by the iconic 1930s dance duo, Fred Astaire and Ginger Rogers, when creating the music video.

FINNEAS and Ashe have previously worked together, most notably on the viral hit “Moral of the Story”, which took off after it’s use in the soundtrack for the Netflix Original movie To All the Boys: P.S. I Still Love You.

annotations: ’Til death do us part

This idiom is most commonly used during traditional wedding vows and the origin of it is uniquely Christian, dating back to 1549, where the pre-altered phrase “till death us depart,” is found in The Book of Common Prayer.

Initially, the phrase didn’t start out as a way to emphasise the importance of making a marriage work. Instead, it quite literally meant that two partners could not be separated for any reason other than death. However, in this context, the line serves as hyperbole for their passionate relationship and wholehearted  love for each other, so long as they’re alive.

If the tide takes California
 I’m so glad I got to hold ya

With rapid climate change in recent years, there has been concern that if all ice in the ocean were to melt that parts of California would be consumed by the ocean. Moreover, the idolization of California and LA in Western media and culture makes this line also symbolic of one failing to achieve their dreams and the end of one’s world that comes along with resigning yourself a life without your passion, or your love (romantic or platonic).

If California sinks, the hub of music, film, and entertainment does as well, creating yet another symbolic death of art and passion.
We’ve been livin’ on a fault line

Ashe and FINNEAS are both from California. California is known for its fault lines, which causes immense earthquakes infrequently. By referencing that both her and FINNEAS are quite literally living on fault lines, she is using earthquakes to symbolize obstacles in a relationship.

annotations: Exaggerated reports of my demise

From the well-known Mark Twain (mis)quotation, “Reports of my death have been greatly exaggerated.”

(This quote has been slightly exaggerated: Twain actually wrote, “The report of my death was an exaggeration.” Full story here.)
If you’ve got a cold starve it, if you’ve got a fever feed it

a sort of role reversal of the popular phrase “ “feed a cold, starve a fever.” This saying has been traced to a 1574 dictionary by John Withals, which noted that “fasting is a great remedy of fever.” The belief is that eating food may help the body generate warmth during a “cold” and that avoiding food may help it cool down when overheated. But recent medical science says the old saw is wrong.
You might be positive and not even know

in the 80s the AIDS epidemic swept across America, with some people not even knowing they were positive with the disease despite not even coming into contact with someone with it.

The title of being “positive” eerily made a recent return, with most of the world been globally infected by COVID-19 during 2020.
Like Steven Seagal I’m Hard to Kill

Hard to Kill is an action film starring Steven Seagal, released in 1990. When adjusted for ticket price inflation, it was the action star’s third highest grossing film, behind the Under Siege movies.

description.plain:
Hope You’re Not Happy is a song written by Ashe for her ex-husband upon realising that she no longer wanted the best for him (unlike in her hit song, Moral of the Story). It is the second release since her debut album, Ashlyn.

Ashe has summarised the single by saying, “Some songs are about moving on and wishing someone the best. This is not that song.” She has also confessed that she hopes “it makes him angry”.

Snippets of Hope You’re Not Happy were first teased on TikTok in late March, with one video reaching over 1.2 million views. Ashe debuted the song on her second headline tour, The Fault Line Tour, over one month ahead of its release on May 6th 2022 (a date decided by her fans during her New York show).

description.plain:
“Save Yourself” serves as a spiteful response to her hit April 2019 single “Moral of the Story” and its success being birthed from her divorce.

This anger Ashe expresses in the song, which weaves its way throughout the lyrics, serves as a “sobering reminder” about the nightmare of the relationship with her ex-husband. By freeing all of her pent up angry feelings towards her then-partner, as well as to herself for ignoring the signs, she is saving herself now when she could not free herself from back then as quickly as she could have.

annotations: So hard to forget it in the morning

If you leave an issue or a problem unresolved from the night before, you tend to mull over it in the morning. Ignoring the red flags don’t stop you from forgetting about them; they might just eat away at you from the start of your day throughout the rest of your week until you find a way to resolve it (if you can). Sometimes we like to sleep things off to try to figure it out later or to forget about it, but that’s often not the case for the latter. In this instance, Ashe might’ve not sent the white flag soaring, but it’s not like she forgot about it; it was on her mind when she wanted to forget, that perhaps leaving was the best thing to do. She knew that the relationship was sinking and there wasn’t anything more to do to save it– but she could save herself from it, which was something that rang loud and true in her mind.
White flag, never sent it soaring

A white flag is the symbol for surrendering and calling a truce. Ashe didn’t file for divorce and walk away from her previous relationship until much later on. When you put so much effort into a relationship (note, “wasted half my twenties”), you kind of want it to end up well. She might’ve thought that if they continued to work through their issues within the relationship or ignored the bad things, then perhaps things would resolve themselves. It’s hard to admit defeat, especially if you once cared for someone a whole lot.
Poured rain all over my sunny

Ashe often describes herself as “pretty fun and bubbly and that’s just [who she is] and [she’s] a super positive, happy girl all the time” (Ashe discusses sharing her pain…Substream Magazine). It’s obvious that her previous relationship caused her a lot of hurt and anger (but also growth!), from songs such as “Moral of the Story” to “Not How It’s Supposed to Go”.

We were cocaine, playing milk and honey
 Dysfunctional, I was a junkie

Tempting something bad with something good, the parallel of cocaine to milk and honey plays into the “junkie” idea in the next line– you might become addicted to the dysfunction, because you’re already so used to it and figure it might not get better than this; the “chaos of the relationship” (“Moral of the Story” annotation, Ashe). The milk and honey might symbolize what was once good in the relationship prior to it breaking down to reveal its true colours– but you go along with it because “you start getting really used to being miserable and thinking that’s normal” (“Moral of the Story” annotation, Ashe).

If I had the chance (Chance)
 I would take it back (Back)
 Jumping off your sinking ship
 ’Stead of going down with it, o

Ashe acknowledges that “we’re all humans and all go through tough times and mess it up” (Ashe discusses sharing her pain…Substream Magazine)– this couldn’t be more true. When you are put in a situation where you believe that you’re in love, you might brush off the supposed red flags as a bump in the road– when in reality, those red flags were there as a way for you to realize that things have gone wrong, and to “jump off [the] sinking ships” to prevent an even worse heartbreak (potentially).
I could’ve saved myself

Ashe had read all of the warning signs but hadn’t “jumped ship” or broken out of the dysfunctional cycle of her previous relationship. She stated that she “knew that [her] marriage was on the verge of collapse. Months later than I should have, I moved out of my house, filed for divorce, and left for tour.” (Ashe reflects on a messy divorce…Ones to Watch) In other words, she could’ve saved herself if she had  acted sooner, but sometimes it’s not so easy to save yourself in these kinds of situations.
Hindsight 2020

This is likely a reference to her divorce as was presented in “Moral of the Story”– in that song, she sings, “Hindsight it’s obvious”. Throughout the rest of “Save Myself”, she keeps highlighting the points where she knew that things were going wrong, and the hindsight was plain for her to see, yet she couldn’t tear herself away from the relationship as quickly as she could have.
